Mons. Desen tot advies dat differente schepe uyt engelant sijn aen gecomen
met de welke seer veel verse gooderen heb ontfangen, oversulx nu meer
versien ben als ojt int jaer waeromme soo ul eenigh dinst konde
daer nu goet sortement soude konnen vinden, dievelk ul tot gpaerme
heb eenige gelt te betaelen aen dengelsche nonnekens tot lenven voor mons
ignatinsclay, soo heb hem een briefken gegeven van een hondert & vijftigh
guldens dwelke ingevalen ul gelegen is te betaelen, en soo niet maeh ul het
selve refuseeren, alsoo niet geirne soeghte disobligeeren middeltijt wensch
ul hier was, om nu goedo provisie van onse goederen te koopen, waerin ul

thd In Antwarp 22 march
S sence my last to you of the 11: curitt. non from you bought the
desired gallicoes to content, I omitted to write, or directs that of the
salempores must be 20 peeces dijed blew of severall culls, darck blew, lighter
& skie cullours a governo: I dare not persuade you to ventes abore 40 or 50
salempores in one bales off cottons att a time, wherefore lett us proceed
here in wisely, & not venter to much and in each vessel butt one bale
yeasterday have sent to newport to m vallego to be sent to you by way
of Dover p direction of m will Eaton one small packett
off laces beeng N1 g 14 parcells as here under, which I wish safe to you
desire you to dispose off itt as best you can to see if any in coridge
to proceed, my next shall carrj the perfect invoyce, whilst now I remaine
London John Loyd
In Antwarp 22 march 1681
S in answer to yd of 4 curitt nothwithstanding you had not the tome to
examine mij invoyce for the 2 packes of tykes, yett supose you will finde no
errour, besides the goods in prijses to content for be confident I could gett
more att present in selling here, then I have noted itt you in beeng don
to continew the correspondency either in halves or for yd acctt. wherefore
lll thanck you in case you please to do mee the favour to send an acc
of the product &bought I want mony in london to pay att the latter
end of aprill & when I wrott you the 8 curits the ex was favorabelde
to mee yett for yd advantidge draw this day att 2 uso to pay to
Henrj Maijnard or order £151:11:10 att 35:6 which I recon is
£269:1:4 in guill ƒ1614:8 which please to accept & paij for yd acctt
itt is as I have remitted with others att 2 uso so exspect to be yd content
I doubt my freind of Gand doth foole mee which I must not wonder
att for wee recon the fleminghs of that nature, when they see aney
more proffitt that then they do not maintaine promise I must be attgad
in few dayes when shall make a dispatch to the legaturen without faille
& so remaine with kinde saluts
In Antwarp 22 march
ondon Henry Maynard
th
Ak
S my last to you was on the 18: curitt sence reed both yd of 4 & 7 ditto as for our
correspondency, Ile considder all towards the latter end of june send an acctt
Generall & endeavour to give you what content you van exspect from
my reasonable freind, when also wee will settle for the future, whilst
pro intrim I'Il see if I shall proceed for my owne & satisfie you for what
shall bepast as well for yd as my acctt. for I must be doing some thing with
you & rather in case our trade then diminish wherefore be confident
Ill not desist from my side to give all due satisfaction. could I butt
be served bij you in northren goods as I have been last yeare by J.V. &
formerly by JK truely I would avoid all mannes of writing to others for
I finde itt more troublesome I have recd. the patternes of N7 the clothes
of which (in case prove as well as the patt. promise) will quit content
itt shall be well thought they were for bridges because rul pindar
is a loading att hull: as to the pack of spanish cloathes you provide
lett itt be sent to bridges also in case this comes no time because wee
made an accommadition with the custome officiers, which other
wise I should have avoided by way of Rotterdam: as for the cottons
to pack in the callicoes, pray lett the bales be butt of peeces as
the last parcell & do not exceed 40 or 50 salempores in one pack & of t
long cloth butt 25„ or 30 peeces and in each vessel that nature
because of late there is seased on one pack, wherefore wee must gett
them over att a longer ruun & be more cautious, which pray observe
benedictus van Claerding is run up to Dunquerque for storme
& hope now att ostend I do exspect to heare of
